And here’s an example of how your JavaScript data object could look:

js
const textData = {
  heroThankYouImage: "./assets/public/thank-you-mobile.jpg",
  thankYouHeroMessage: "Your copy of Ebook 1: Steps 1-4: From Powerlessness to Awareness – A Modern Guide to the First Four Steps is on its way to your inbox right now.",

And a little helper script to populate the HTML:

js
document.querySelectorAll("[data-text]").forEach(el => {
  const key = el.getAttribute("data-text");
  if (textData[key]) {
    el.textContent = textData[key];
  }
});

document.querySelectorAll("[data-img]").forEach(el => {
  const key = el.getAttribute("data-img");
  if (textData[key]) {
    el.setAttribute("src", textData[key]);
  }
});

Dito pelo ChatGPT:

You’ve got two issues:

  1. Wrong script paths — you’re loading config/*.js, but your files live under assets/config/*.js.

  2. data-img="optinPage.bgImgKey" is a path, not an image key. Your current window.IMAGES is a flat key→URL map. Putting optinPage inside IMAGES (as an object of pointers) won’t resolve to URLs unless your apply script knows how to (a) read from TEXTS and (b) dereference the pointer to an IMAGES key.

Here’s a clean, working setup.

1) Fix your <script> paths

Replace these four tags in <head>:

html
<!-- ✅ correct, in this order -->
<script src="assets/config/images.config.js" defer></script>
<script src="assets/config/images.apply.js" defer></script>
<script src="assets/config/texts.config.js" defer></script>
<script src="assets/config/texts.apply.js" defer></script>

2) Keep IMAGES flat only

Do not nest optinPage inside window.IMAGES. Make IMAGES just a key→URL dictionary:

js
// assets/config/images.config.js
window.IMAGES = {
  favicon32: "assets/public/logo.png",
  favicon48: "assets/public/logo.png",
  favicon64: "assets/public/logo.png",

  logo: "assets/public/logo.png",
  heroBg: "assets/public/priscilla-du-preez-F9DFuJoS9EU-unsplash.jpg",

  time: "assets/public/time.png",
  forbes: "assets/public/forbes.jpg",
  bbc: "assets/public/bbc.png",
  rollingStone: "assets/public/rolling-stone.png",
  nationalGeo: "assets/public/national-geographic.png",

  firstPhoto: "assets/public/woman-learning.jpg",
  secondPhoto: "assets/public/AA.JPG",
  thirdPhoto: "assets/public/pensive.jpg",

  calendlyPhoto: "assets/public/sample-offer.png",
  testimonialBg: "https://images.clickfunnels.com/1a/f29ad03b2011e990d4779bdb624161/lp-testimonial-bg.jpg",
  fourthPhoto: "assets/public/eBook-guarated.png",
  fifthPhoto: "assets/public/mountain.JPG"

3) Put your page pointers in TEXTS

4) Make images.apply.js handle dot-paths and pointers

This tiny helper lets data-img="optinPage.bgImgKey" work by:

  • Reading window.TEXTS.optinPage.bgImgKey → "heroBg"

  • Looking up window.IMAGES["heroBg"] → URL

  • Falling back gracefully if you pass a direct IMAGES key

html
<!-- assets/config/images.apply.js -->
<script>
(function () {
  function getByPath(root, path) {
    return path.split('.').reduce((acc, k) => (acc && acc[k] != null ? acc[k] : undefined), root);
  }

  function resolveImage(attrValue) {
    // If the attribute is a dot-path, try TEXTS first (it should contain a key like "heroBg")
    if (attrValue.includes('.')) {
      const keyFromTexts = getByPath(window.TEXTS || {}, attrValue);
      if (keyFromTexts && window.IMAGES && window.IMAGES[keyFromTexts]) return window.IMAGES[keyFromTexts];
      // also allow a direct URL in TEXTS
      if (typeof keyFromTexts === 'string' && /^https?:|^\/|\.\/|^\.\.\//.test(keyFromTexts)) return keyFromTexts;
    }
    // Otherwise, treat the attr as an IMAGES key directly
    if (window.IMAGES && window.IMAGES[attrValue]) return window.IMAGES[attrValue];
    // Finally, if the attr itself looks like a URL/path, use it as-is
    if (/^https?:|^\/|\.\/|^\.\.\//.test(attrValue)) return attrValue;
    return null;
  }

  function applyImages() {
    const nodes = document.querySelectorAll('[data-img]');
    nodes.forEach(el => {
      const token = el.getAttribute('data-img');
      const url = resolveImage(token);
      if (url) {
        if (el.tagName === 'IMG') {
          el.setAttribute('src', url);
        } else {
          // for non-IMG elements, assume background-image usage if desired later
          el.style.backgroundImage = `url("${url}")`;
        }
      } else {
        console.warn('[images.apply] could not resolve', token);
      }
    });
  }

  if (document.readyState === 'loading') {
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', applyImages);
  } else {
    applyImages();
  }
})();
</script>

B. Upgrade texts.apply.js to support inputs & dot paths

Drop this in /assets/config/texts.apply.js (or merge into your existing file). It:

  • Resolves dot paths like optinHero.form.submitLabel from window.TEXTS

  • Sets textContent for normal elements

  • Sets placeholder for text/email/tel inputs

  • Sets value for submit/button inputs

  • Supports optional data-html to use innerHTML (for strings containing <strong>, etc.)

html
<script>
(function () {
  // Safely resolve TEXTS dot-paths like "optinHero.form.submitLabel"
  function getByPath(root, path) {
    return path.split('.').reduce((acc, key) => (acc && acc[key] != null ? acc[key] : undefined), root);
  }

  function applyTexts() {
    const TEXTS = window.TEXTS || {};
    // 1) data-html first: allows HTML markup in the string (innerHTML)
    document.querySelectorAll('[data-html]').forEach(el => {
      const key = el.getAttribute('data-html');
      const val = getByPath(TEXTS, key);
      if (typeof val === 'string') el.innerHTML = val;
    });

    // 2) data-text: default behavior
    document.querySelectorAll('[data-text]').forEach(el => {
      const key = el.getAttribute('data-text');
      const val = getByPath(TEXTS, key);
      if (val == null) return;

      const tag = el.tagName.toLowerCase();
      if (tag === 'input') {
        const type = (el.getAttribute('type') || '').toLowerCase();
        if (type === 'submit' || type === 'button' || type === 'reset') {
          el.value = String(val);
        } else {
          // text, email, tel, etc. → placeholder
          el.setAttribute('placeholder', String(val));
        }
      } else if (tag === 'textarea') {
        el.setAttribute('placeholder', String(val));
      } else {
        // everything else → textContent
        el.textContent = String(val);
      }
    });
  }

  if (document.readyState === 'loading') {
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', applyTexts);
  } else {
    applyTexts();
  }
})();
</script>

Tip: for strings that include HTML (e.g., in your thankYou.tooCurious texts with <strong>), use data-html="path.to.key" instead of data-text.
